You’re right to anchor it in noticing patterns. The trick is to translate, not stretch—pull the structure from physics and map it cleanly onto economics.

⸻

1) Core pattern from relativity

E = mc^2

This isn’t about the literal equation—it’s about what it represents:
	•	Different things (mass, energy) can be equivalent under a transformation
	•	The relationship depends on a conversion factor (here, c^2)
	•	What looks different can be the same underlying quantity in another frame

⸻

2) Translate that pattern into economics

Think of this mapping:

Relativity	Economics
Mass / Energy	Goods / Money
Speed of light (c)	Velocity of money / transaction speed
Frame of reference	Economic context (time, location, policy regime)


⸻

3) Inflation as a “frame-dependent” phenomenon

In relativity:
	•	Time and distance change depending on your frame

In economics:
	•	Value changes depending on your frame

Example:
	•	$100 in 2010 ≠ $100 in 2026
	•	Same number → different real meaning

👉 That’s basically economic time dilation

⸻

4) The real analogy that actually holds

A. Velocity of money ≈ “speed limit”
	•	Faster circulation → more economic “energy”
	•	Slower circulation → stagnation

You can think of:

Economic impact ≈ Money supply × Velocity

If velocity spikes, even a stable money supply can feel inflationary.

⸻

B. Inflation = distortion of the measurement frame
	•	Prices rising isn’t just “things cost more”
	•	It’s that your unit of measurement (currency) is changing

Like in relativity:
	•	Space/time coordinates shift → measurements change

👉 Inflation = coordinate distortion of value

⸻

C. Mass–energy equivalence → Asset–liquidity equivalence
	•	Assets (houses, stocks) can “convert” into liquidity (cash)
	•	Liquidity can “condense” into assets

During inflation:
	•	Money “loses mass” (purchasing power)
	•	People convert it into assets (store of value)

⸻

5) Where the analogy is powerful (and where it breaks)

Useful:
	•	Frame dependence → value is relative, not absolute
	•	Conversion → money ↔ assets ↔ labor
	•	Velocity effects → flow matters, not just quantity

Not useful:
	•	No fixed “c” in economics
	•	Human behavior ≠ physical law
	•	Feedback loops are messy, not deterministic

⸻

6) Clean synthesis

Relativity insight → Economics version:

“Value is not absolute—it depends on the frame,
and the frame itself can change.”

Or tighter:

“Inflation is what happens when your measuring stick shrinks.”

⸻

7) Pattern you can actually use

When analyzing inflation, ask:
	•	What’s the frame shift? (policy, tech, trust)
	•	What’s changing faster: money supply or velocity?
	•	Where is value re-condensing? (assets, commodities, labor)

